================================================================================
In-house clean-room parsers (LogQL, TraceQL)
================================================================================

Cerberus's LogQL parser (internal/logql/lsyntax, internal/logql/logpattern,
internal/drain) and TraceQL parser (internal/traceql/ast) are original,
independent reimplementations written by the Cerberus authors from the
published LogQL and TraceQL language grammars and HTTP API documentation. They
are not derived from, and do not copy source code from, Grafana Loki or Grafana
Tempo, with one narrow exception: a small set of error-message strings is
deliberately reproduced verbatim so that Cerberus returns wire-compatible error
text to clients (each such string is documented at its definition site).

These parsers are API-compatible with Grafana Loki and Grafana Tempo so that
Cerberus can act as a drop-in datasource. "Loki", "Tempo", "Grafana",
"Prometheus", "PromQL", "LogQL", and "TraceQL" are used here nominatively, only
to identify the query languages and wire formats Cerberus is compatible with.
Cerberus is not affiliated with, sponsored by, or endorsed by Grafana Labs, the
Prometheus project, or the OpenTelemetry project.

The reference Grafana Loki (github.com/grafana/loki) and Grafana Tempo
(github.com/grafana/tempo) query parsers are licensed under the GNU Affero
General Public License v3.0 (AGPLv3). Cerberus does NOT link or distribute those
parsers in its binary. They are referenced only by build-tagged, test-only
fidelity oracles and the differential compatibility harnesses, which are
isolated in the test/oracle nested Go module and never compiled into the
shipped cmd/cerberus binary. The agpl-clean CI gate
(.github/scripts/agpl-clean.mjs) enforces this.

